                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12421942" author="djd" created="Tue, 18 Jul 2006 21:25:01 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Possible workaround is for the application to use getCharacterStream and apply encoding as required.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12499052" author="kristwaa" created="Fri, 25 May 2007 12:37:07 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Would people object to just changing the encoding in the client from US-ASCII to ISO-8859-1?&lt;br/&gt;
This would make Derby more compliant with JDBC, but could it also break existing applications?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have checked that the change does not break any tests for Clob, but it remains to see if the same is true for PreparedStatement.setAsciiStream (on the client).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12499451" author="knutanders" created="Sun, 27 May 2007 23:01:14 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;+1 to change the encoding on the client to ISO-8859-1. Sounds like a safe change that is not likely to break existing applications.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12500411" author="kristwaa" created="Thu, 31 May 2007 17:58:44 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;&apos;derby-1519-1a.diff&apos; changes all uses of US-ASCII on the client to ISO-8859-1.&lt;br/&gt;
suites.All run without errors with Java 1.5, and I started a derbyall now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please raise your concerns if you have any, I will commit if the second test run goes well.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12500598" author="kristwaa" created="Fri, 1 Jun 2007 08:33:11 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;derbyall ran without failures.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12501239" author="kristwaa" created="Mon, 4 Jun 2007 16:11:18 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Draft of a potential release note, if required. Checkbox for release note not ticked yet...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12501267" author="myrna" created="Mon, 4 Jun 2007 17:56:37 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;The release note looks fine, except for the &apos;obtain&apos; in the summary I&lt;br/&gt;
think should be &apos;obtained&apos;.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;I guess I don&apos;t really understand the possible impact.&lt;br/&gt;
Would the same characters would now be displayed whereas previously&lt;br/&gt;
you&apos;d see question marks? Isn&apos;t whether you see question marks or not&lt;br/&gt;
depending on the console encoding you have set?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Or is the actual difference something else?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It seems to me wiser to add a release note for a possible incompatibility.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Myrna&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12501478" author="kristwaa" created="Tue, 5 Jun 2007 08:49:01 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Ticked the &quot;Release Note Needed&quot; flag, and added 10.3 to the affected list.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t think the release note can be called fine, if people don&apos;t understand what it means. I&apos;ll have given it another try.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This time I deleted the old file, but what is the preferred way of publishing updates to the release note?&lt;br/&gt;
Must the file be named something special for the utility to pick it up?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12501479" author="kristwaa" created="Tue, 5 Jun 2007 08:50:52 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Second version of the release notes.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12501492" author="kristwaa" created="Tue, 5 Jun 2007 10:00:48 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Committed &apos;derby-1519-1a.diff&apos; to trunk with revision 544424. Ran suites.All with Java 1.5 again cleanly.&lt;br/&gt;
Based on the possible incompatibilities, I suppose the right think to do is not to merge this with the 10.2 (or 10.1)  branch?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Should we also tick the existing application impact?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12501612" author="myrna" created="Tue, 5 Jun 2007 17:58:28 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;The new release note is more explicit, I like it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The release note file has to be named releaseNote.html.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The release note generator (see &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/DERBY-2750&quot; title=&quot;Convert lang/declareGlobalTempTableJava.java to JUnit&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;DERBY-2750&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;DERBY-2750&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;) will figure out the latest&lt;br/&gt;
file of that name &amp;amp; pick that one, so you don&apos;t need to remove the old&lt;br/&gt;
one.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The release note generator will pick up the release notes whenever&lt;br/&gt;
it&apos;s marked release note needed or existing application impact, but&lt;br/&gt;
some people have ticked release note needed off when they attach a&lt;br/&gt;
release note, and leave existing application impact on.&lt;br/&gt;
So, probably best to tick &apos;application impact&apos;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Myrna&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12501614" author="djd" created="Tue, 5 Jun 2007 18:03:49 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;The change is only for the client driver correct? If so the release note should be explicit about that.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12501696" author="kristwaa" created="Tue, 5 Jun 2007 22:35:08 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Your comment makes a lot of sense Dan &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.gif&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt; Thanks!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have uploaded a third revision of the release notes. It is now considered done from my point of view, but others are free to change it if they feel the need to.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12501699" author="kristwaa" created="Tue, 5 Jun 2007 22:37:28 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Ticked &quot;Existing Application Impact&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thank you Myrna for your input on this, and for reading the release notes.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12506358" author="myrna" created="Wed, 20 Jun 2007 02:40:38 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;adding &apos;Release Note Needed&apos; flag so this gets picked up by the ReleaseNotesGenerator.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12506425" author="kristwaa" created="Wed, 20 Jun 2007 08:17:40 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;This is an easy fix to merge into the 10.2 branch, but is that safe/correct to do?&lt;br/&gt;
If not, I will close this issue.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12533100" author="kristwaa" created="Mon, 8 Oct 2007 12:19:17 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Since there has been no response on merging the fix with 10.2 and we have pushed 10.3 out the door, I&apos;m closing this issue without merging it with the 10.2 branch.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
